First off, props to the title for the movie. A title this extraordinary warrants immediate interest. I knew nothing about the movie going in and I'm glad for it; the defining point for this movie, the vampire haunting Bad City, has a fantastic reveal that launches the movie from a lull to enthralling. For that twist alone, it is worth seeing this movie just for the same rush of emotion. (To be honest, I didn't even know the movie had a vampire in it, that's how little I knew about it).

All of that being said, the black and white color scheme and the surreal style give off a David Lynch-like vibe, similar to Eraserhead. This pays off with some genuinely creepy and scary moments, but a lot of the time it comes off as camp and ridiculous. One scene meant to unsettle and disturb can be followed up with something eliciting laughter. Then again, the setting is called Bad City, and one character met early on is some wannabe gangster type, with the mannerisms to match.

The odd tone likely comes from being less of a horror movie and more like a drama with horror elements. There's a lot more focus on character interaction and conflict between them than actually trying to scare you, which makes for a compelling story. But then it will draw away from that to show clips of oil pumps or a person playing with a balloon. These diversions could be rationalized as establishing traits of the aforementioned "Bad City", but they distract from a movie that's mostly spent dealing with its character's vices. Some plot elements partially distract as well, in particular one point where the movie probably feels they used Chekov's Gun adequately, only to add to the overall absurdity up to that point.

I did enjoy the horror this movie had to offer, and I especially enjoyed the prominent attention to characters, but the flippant tone and oddball content draw too much from the story and how much of an effect it could've had. I've seen the movie called "style over substance", which is somewhat fitting; there's plenty of both here, but the style takes the center of attention more often than not. The movie still interested me from beginning to end, and I'm anticipating whatever future work the director (Ana Lily Amirpour) will put out next.
